headline: The strange airborne rescue of Gaza's donkeys, from Israel to Europe
subhead: Since 2022, Sharon Cohen, who runs an animal rescue group near Tel Aviv, has removed donkeys from Palestinian owners she accuses of mistreatment and sent them to shelters across Europe. The initiative has drawn outrage amid Gaza's deepening humanitarian crisis.

Europe will 'stand united' in response to Trump's tariff threats over Greenland
Amichai Chikli, the Israeli diaspora affairs minister who defies the Jewish diaspora
subhead: Appointed by Benjamin Netanyahu to oversee Israel's relations with the Jewish diaspora, Chikli has displayed close ties to the French far right while urging Jews worldwide to move to Israel as soon as possible, writes historian Jean-Pierre Filiu.

headline: Russian militarization of winter hardens resolve in Kyiv: 'We're freezing, but we won't give in'
subhead: Daily Russian attacks on energy infrastructure have left residents of the Ukrainian capital without electricity and heating as temperatures drop to −15°C. The strategy does not appear to have dampened Kyivans' spirits.

headline: Gen Z thirsts for a digital detox: 'I felt bad after every use, quitting lifted a huge weight off me'
subhead: More and more young people are feeling dependent on their screens, and taking steps to regain control over their digital device use by deleting social media apps and limiting their screen time.

headline: Iranian artists exiled in France voice distress over massacres
subhead: Petrified by the horror stories coming out of the country, Iranian artists living in exile in France keep a close eye on their home. They worry about their loved ones and eagerly await rare news, which is often relayed by someone lucky enough to escape the internet blackout.

subhead: The president of the far-right Rassemblement National presents himself as the 'authentic spokesperson for a France despised by the elites,' yet was photographed in the company of the daughter of Prince Carlo of Bourbon-Two Sicilies, Duke of Castro.

headline: Henrique Gouveia e Melo, the admiral who wants to lead Portugal
subhead: Revealed during the Covid-19 pandemic, former military officer Henrique Gouveia e Melo is in the race for the January 18 presidential election. He has attracted voters with his talk of reform, despite his limited grasp of political conventions.

headline: In Libya's desert, Sudanese refugees cross paths as they flee or return to their homeland
subhead: Between 350,000 and one million Sudanese refugees have arrived in Libya since the outbreak of war in April 2023. In the southern city of Kufra, refugees end up in unsanitary camps. With no prospects, some decide to return to Sudan, despite the horrors of the fighting.
